			<section class="part" id="entry-and-exit">
				<h1>Entry and exit</h1>
				<h2>Passport validity</h2>
				<p>Your passport should be valid for a minimum of 6 months from the date you enter Egypt.</p>

				<h2>Visa</h2>
				<p>British passport holders normally need a visa. You can buy one on arrival, if you’re staying less than 30 days.
				Or you can get a visa from an Egyptian Consulate before you go.</p>
				<p>If you’re visiting Sharm El Sheikh, Dahab, Nuweiba or Taba for less than 15 days, you’ll get a free entry permission stamp on arrival.
				But you must get a visa, if you want to stay longer than 15 days or travel out of these resorts. You can normally buy one at Sharm El Sheikh airport.</p>

				<h2>UK Emergency Travel Documents</h2>
				<p>You can use a UK Emergency Travel Document (ETD) to leave Egypt. But you can’t use one to enter the country.</p>

				<h2>Yellow fever</h2>
				<p>You must show proof of a yellow fever vaccination if arriving from countries with risk of yellow fever. </p>

				<h2>Previous travel to Israel</h2>
				<p>You won’t normally have problems entering Egypt if you have an Israeli stamp in your passport.  </p>

				<h2>Work permits</h2>
				<p>You must show evidence of HIV testing if you’re applying for a work permit. </p>
			</section>

			<section class="part" id="safety-and-security">
				<h1>Safety and security</h1>
				<h2>Detailed summary</h2>
				<!-- <p id="no-travel">Travel not advised info</p>
