				<h2>Protests</h2>
				<p>Many people have died in violent clashes since President Morsi was removed from office in July 2013. Protests often happen on Fridays but can also happen at any time with little notice.</p>
				<p>Police may use water cannon, tear gas, birdshot or live ammunition for crowd control. Don’t cross roadblocks put up by the security forces or protesters.</p>
				<p>Protestors have singled out westerners, including Britons. Most clashes have taken place in Cairo, Alexandria and Fayoum but are common across Egypt including:</p>
				<ul>
					<li>Assyut</li>
					<li>Suez</li>
					<li>Ismaliyya</li>
					<li>Mansoura</li>
				</ul>

				<h2>Terrorism</h2>
				<p>There is a high threat from terrorism.</p>
				<p>Security is tight throughout the country, especially in resort areas but the risk of attack is high, even in public places used by tourists.</p>

				<h2>Crime</h2>
				<p>The crime rate remains generally low, but security is affected by the current political unrest.</p>
				<p>Report a crime to the police immediately. Failure to report crimes before you leave Egypt will make it impossible to seek a prosecution at a later date.</p>

				<h2>Sexual crime</h2>
				<p>There’s a serious risk of violence and sexual assault at demonstrations, with reports of around 100 rapes and sexual assaults since June 2013.</p>
				<p>Sexual assaults have taken place in hotels, in taxis and on microbuses.</p>
			</section>

			<section class="part" id="local-laws">
				<h1>Local laws</h1>
				<h2>Alcohol and drugs</h2>
				<p>You can be arrested for drinking alcohol in the street or anywhere apart from a licensed restaurant or bar.
				You may face life imprisonment or the death penalty for using, possession or trafficking of illegal drugs. </p>
				<h2>ID</h2>
				<p>Carry photo ID with you at all times.</p>
				<h2>Photography</h2>
				<p>Taking photos of or near military installations is strictly prohibited, including the Suez Canal.  Don’t photograph officials without their consent.  British nationals have been arrested for photographing electricity stations and train stations. </p>
				<h2>Homosexuality</h2>
				<p>Although homosexuality is not illegal under Egyptian law, homosexual acts in public are illegal and gay people have been convicted for breaching laws on public decency.</p>
				<h2>Religion</h2>
				<p>Encouraging conversion to the Christian faith is against the law.</p>
			</section>

			<section class="part" id="health">
				<h1>Health</h1>
				<p>For health advice on Egypt, visit the National Travel Health Network and Centre.</p>
				<p>Medical facilities outside Cairo, major cities and resorts can be basic.  In an emergency, seek treatment in Cairo or the nearest big city or town.
				In an emergency dial 123 and ask for an ambulance.
				Pre-travel Hepatitis A vaccine is now recommended for all travellers.
				Information about healthcare abroad, including a country-by-country guide to reciprocal healthcare agreements with the UK, is available from <a href="http://www.nhs.uk">NHS Choices</a>.</p>
			</section>

